\section{Sheaf cohomology with $\ModuleCat k$ coefficients}
\label{sec:HModule}

Mathlib provides $\Sheaf.\mathtt{H} \,\colon\, \Sheaf\,J\,\AddCommGrpCat \to \mathbb N \to \mathrm{Type}\,\_$ — an abstract Grothendieck-topology cohomology in $\AddCommGrpCat$. The value category is fixed to $\AddCommGrpCat$; there is no $\ModuleCat k$-flavoured analogue in Mathlib. The iter-009 finding (logged in \texttt{task\_pending.md}) is that closing $\genus C$ honestly as $\dim_k H^1(C, \struct C)$ requires a parallel sheaf cohomology valued in $\ModuleCat k$ rather than $\AddCommGrpCat$, since $\Module.\mathtt{finrank}\,k$ requires a $\Module k$ structure that the $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued $\Sheaf.\mathtt H$ cannot provide.

The construction is short. The $\Linear k$-enriched abelian category $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat k)$ already has $\HasExt$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}), and $\Ext$ groups in any $\Linear k$ abelian category carry a canonical $\Module k$ structure via \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.instModule}. We mirror $\Sheaf.\mathtt H$'s standard construction $\Ext(\mathtt{constantSheaf}.\mathrm{obj}\,1, F, n)$ with $\AddCommGrpCat$ replaced by $\ModuleCat k$ and the unit object $1$ replaced by $\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k$.

\begin{definition}[Sheaf cohomology with $\ModuleCat k$ coefficients]
  \label{def:Scheme_HModule}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule}
  \uses{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK, thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a category with $J : \mathrm{GrothendieckTopology}\,C$, and assume $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)$ and $\HasExt(\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k))$. For $F : \Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$ and $n \in \mathbb N$, define the $\ModuleCat k$-flavoured sheaf cohomology
  \[
    \mathtt{HModule}\,k\,F\,n \;:=\; \Ext\bigl((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k),\ F,\ n\bigr),
  \]
  where $\Ext$ is the standard \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext} construction. This is automatically a $\Module k$-module via \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.instModule}.
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}[Choice of \texttt{abbrev} over \texttt{def}]
  The Lean implementation uses \lstinline{noncomputable abbrev} rather than \lstinline{noncomputable def}. The reason is that instance synthesis must see through the wrapper to find the $\Module\,k$ and $\AddCommGroup$ instances on the underlying $\Ext$ group. A \lstinline{def} blocks unfolding, and the iter-009 plan-agent probe verified that \lstinline{Module k (HModule k F n)} fails to synthesize (\texttt{failed to synthesize instance of type class AddCommMonoid}) under \lstinline{def}. Switching to \lstinline{abbrev} makes the wrapper reducible, and instance synthesis succeeds for both $\Module\,k$ and $\AddCommGroup$. The \lstinline{noncomputable} modifier is required because \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.instModule} is itself noncomputable.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}[Universe parameters]
  The signature mirrors Mathlib's \lstinline{Sheaf.H} \[\{C : \mathrm{Type}\,u_4\}\,[\Category.\{u_3, u_4\}\,C]\,\{J : \mathrm{GrothendieckTopology}\,C\}\,(F : \Sheaf\,J\,\AddCommGrpCat) \dots\] using fully general universes $\{u, v\}$: the morphism universe of $C$ is pinned to $u$ to match $\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k$, the object universe of $C$ is left as $v$. For the project's primary use case ($J = \opens.\mathrm{grothendieckTopology}\,X.\mathrm{toTopCat}$ with $X : \Scheme.\{u\}$), one has $v = u$ and $\Category.\{u, u\}$. The iter-009 plan-agent probe verified both the abstract general-$v$ case and the concrete $v = u$ specialisation.
\end{remark}

\section{Use in the project}

The composition of the four typeclass instances of Sections~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}–\ref{sec:moduleK_ext}, Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}, and Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule} delivers Phase~A step~5 in full and bridges to Phase~A step~6:

\begin{itemize}
  \item For $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat\,k))$, the $\ModuleCat\,k$-flavoured cohomology
    \[
      H^n_{\Module\,k}(C, \struct C) \;:=\; \mathtt{HModule}\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,n
    \]
    is well-defined and automatically carries a $\Module\,k$ instance, so $\Module.\mathtt{finrank}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1) : \mathbb N$ is well-defined.
  \item The forgetful functor $\ModuleCat\,k \to \AddCommGrpCat$ recovers the iter-004 abelian-group cohomology (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf_forgetCompare}), so the new $\HModule$ commutes with the existing $\Sheaf.\mathtt H$ on the underlying type level.
  \item Phase~A step~6 (Serre finiteness, $\finrank_k H^i(C, \mathcal F) < \infty$) remains the deep work to come, but is now expressible inside Mathlib's standard $\Module\,k$ API: the statement of Serre finiteness becomes a $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,F\,n)$ predicate.
\end{itemize}

